<title>The Mantis and the Great Tortoise </title>
<summary>|kaggen (the Mantis) strokes the neck of the Great Tortoise and she pulls her head  into her neck hole, so his arms get stuck and decay. |kaggen tells a lizard (the !khauw) to rub the Great Tortoise&apos;s neck and the Great Tortoise pulls her head in again (story continues largely untranslated). |kaggen flies into the water (as a vulture) where the water washes off his &apos;arms&apos; feathers&apos; and he becomes a man again and returns home (see 859v) where he is counselled by the Ichneumon. Thereafter is an account of how he dreams and gets &apos;understanding&apos;s thoughts&apos; and becomes an &apos;understanding&apos;s person&apos;. <i>... a story describing how the Mantis is tricked by the Great Tortoise (L II.-5.  565-624, 8. 811-882).  This is followed by a discourse upon the degrees of understanding possessed by various animals (L II.-8.  822-892). </i></summary><comments>1) Dates on p.572: 11 October; p.811: 15 November; p.870: 20 November, 2) p.598v: |kaggen is stupid on his one side but clever on his other (the Dutch word <i>schelm</i> is used), 3) p.815v: a red poison, 4) p.816v: |kaggen&apos;s stealing of another man&apos;s things, 5) p.859v: the |xam and Dutch names for the korhaan and vulture, 6) p.862v: notes on the &apos;angry man&apos; and the &apos;bow man&apos; (|kaggen) who cannot deceive others and who then gets thoughts in his dreams, 7) p.863v: snakes and the mouse eaten by this person (the &apos;angry&apos; or &apos;bow&apos; man, or |kaggen), 8) p.864v: an animal that makes its house from bushes and whose back hair and front teeth are like the dassie&apos;s; types of mice and snakes, 9) p.865v: the place in the throat where thoughts are found, 10) p.868v: the person who does not &apos;understand&apos; or &apos;get thoughts&apos; (|kaggen); the |ni (the Ichneumon) does &apos;understand&apos; a lot, 11) This story is found in Books II-5 and II-8</comments><date>October – November 1871</date><storypages>565-624, 811-882</storypag